					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Being a PC Merchant</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:krunch@netbuilders.net">Kruunch</a> | 
		            12/14/1999 5:47:34 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">(This post will be OOC as it may get lengthy) - Hi all, this is your guide to the most rewarding and profitable trade bar NONE! If you are from the Brell Serellis server you either know me, have dealt with me, or have at least seen one of my auctions (if not multiple auctions ;). Since being a PC merchant has made me a rich man (comparatively) I wanted to share some of my experiences and advice with other budding merchants and people who want to do well in general (whether it be garnering that rare item, making a ton of plats, or making a ton of friends). I've broken this guide down into four parts: Buying, Selling, Trading, and Etiquette. Hope you enjoy and prosper :)<BR>
<BR>
BUYING: The mistake most people make when buying an item is not knowing what its' market worth is. Never buy an item that you haven't seen auctioned before or without checking with 3 seperate sources. Too many times I've seen people lured into buying a Screaming Mace for 250 PP in Qeynos. Never buy and item you're ULTRA hot for. This is sort of like food shopping when you're hungry. Patience is the name of the game, and eventually the right price always (and I mean 100% of the time) comes along. Also, it's a little known trick in EQ that you do pretty much just as well with the current items you own, as opposed to the ones you want. Another trick to successful purchasing for yourself, or for resale is buying where the item is dropped. For instance, buying bronze armor in Unrest for 10 PP a piece and reselling it in freeport for 25 PP per piece. Remember, alot of items have less value to certain people then others. High level characters will sometimes destroy bronze armor as it weighs too much. A merchant at the right place and time will find a GREAT bargain time and again. I routinely buy Jagged Bands in Unrest for 50 PP and sell them in Oasis for 125 PP. One rule of thumb... NEVER pay &quot;standard&quot; prices for an item.<BR>
<BR>
SELLING: When selling an item you don't need to be everyone's best friend or try and conive a person into a sale. Items sell themselves really in EQ. The higher end the item, the less talking you have to do. And remember, the term &quot;high end&quot; is subjective. Banded armor is high end stuff to an 6th level warrior. Also, have a great deal of patience. For every good customer you have, you will have at least 5 people with silly offers or questions ad nauseum. Be patient and polite at all times (being friendly is even better). Answer all questions, and never ignore a tell (even the stupid ones). Always inflate your prices just a little (10% or so) so you have room to haggle (many is the time I made a sale because I came down 5 PP on a 100 PP item). You will eventually recieve tells telling you how much you're a &quot;rip-off&quot; and that you're gouging. Remember to be polite and patient (even to the point of being absurdly polite). I find roleplaying haggling one of the funnest parts of EQ and have made many a sell because &quot;me poor kids be starvin' in da tenaments o' Free Port!&quot;. Now this next part is VERY important: don't be GREEDY. Although you will be accused of this many a time, if you actually try and sell at outrageous prices, or worse, take advantage of someone's ignorance, you will start making enemies, and enemies are the anethma to being a merchant. If someone wants to pay you 100 PP for that Langseax, politely inform them that they are offering too much and sell it for 40 PP. You're still getting a great deal and are making a friend in the process. I personally sell most of my items at high end prices, however I NEVER would brag about selling an MM shield for a 1000 PP (and I've been offered this once and sold it for 400 PP which was still a tad high). If you're selling multiple items to one person, cut them a break. Every person likes to feel like they're getting a deal.<BR>
<BR>
TRADING: One of the best aspects of EQ is trading for an item. This stage of the game takes a practiced eye and knowledge of worth and items to be done successfully. First, have a purpose to the trade. Are you making a profit? Can you sell what you just traded for? Do you have a customer lines up for this item? Most times when I get trades, it's usually in combination with platinum. Many is the time the person is a few platinum short and instead of telling them to take a hike, I ask them if they have something to kick in for trade on top of the deal? This works wonders! You will find that you get more then you originally wanted and again, you've made a customer happy (and happy customers in EQ come back to do you great favors). When trading item for item, know the worth in PP of each. There is usually a range in worth (like a Shiney Brass Halberd runs 80 PP - 125 PP) and always use the low end price when quoting its worth (this is sort of like the red book - blue book thing car dealerships do). You will find that the worth of an item is increased, when it's sold or traded in another land. Lockjaw Vests go for 35-40 PP in Oasis, where they are dropped but sell easily for 65 PP in Greater Faydark or Qeynos. Never let a trader go away mad. ALways be friendly and consoling, especially if a trade didn't go through (even if you're the one who is mad). There are a few people on my server who always have great stuff but that I never deal with (and neither do most people) because they have really bad attitudes. I'd rather cut my profit margin and have a successful trade or sale, then to squeeze every plat out of a person, and have them go away with a bad taste in their mouths.<BR>
<BR>
ETIQUETTE: This is the art of just having good manners. Say please and thank you. Throw in a smiley emoti-con from time to time (they're free after all ;). Don't abuse the ignorance of a customer, while at the same time to chastise or worse, get flaming mad at the ignorance of a customer. Some people will curse you out, tell you that you are insane, etc... Be polite and FRIENDLY. Even absurdly so. Always respond to a tell (even the stupid ones). ALways try to make the deal happen. Yes this all sounds time consuming, but so is any trade. But there is no law against auctioning in a zone you're fighting in either ;)<BR>
<BR>
MONEY MAKING TIPS: Selling Crush Bone belts and pads (5th-15th level can bring in up to 20 plats per hour). Hunting wisps for Greater Lightstones (10th-18th lvl need magic weapon. Can make up to 250 PP per day). Reselling Bronze armor, Thick Aprons, and Jagged Bands bought cheaply at Unrest (any level, need some capital for this). Buying Fine Steel weapons for 2 PP each at Unrest, Sol A, Lake Rathe, Permafrost, Splitpaw or Mist Moore and selling to merchant (any level but need a high CHA character to sell to merchants... can make 500 PP a day).<BR>
<BR>
Hope this guide helps you. To give you an idea of what you can gain this is my current inventory at 26th level:<BR>
<BR>
Ghoulbane<BR>
Cracked Dark Shield<BR>
Charred Guardian Breast Plate<BR>
Rubicite Greaves<BR>
Steel Vambraces<BR>
Darkmail Gauntlets<BR>
Blackened Iron Crown<BR>
Plat Rings<BR>
Black Pearl Choker<BR>
Serpant Bracers (or Golden Jaded depending on my mood ;)<BR>
Dwarven Workboots<BR>
Lizardscale Cloak<BR>
Grotesque Mask<BR>
Crested Spaulder<BR>
Heavy Recurve Bow<BR>
Thick Leather Apron<BR>
Plat earrings<BR>
<BR>
Enjoy ;)<BR>
<BR>
Kruunch Spiritslammer (Ugliest Paladin o' Kaladim)<BR>
&lt;26th order - Legion of Heroes&gt;<BR>
Master Merchant and Smithy<BR>
Veteran Brewer and Tailor<BR>
etc, etc, etc....<BR>
<BR>
krunch@netbuilders.net
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
