	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Lovely guide. I myself have recently become a merchant in EQ, and am pleased with my success. I was able to start with a good amount of capital, 8kpp (I was lucky and won a roll on iksar berserker club in Kurns tower), but in just 2 weeks I'd say my net worth is about 14-18k. <BR>
<BR>
Here are a few thing's I've learned being a merchant in EQ, and some of which has been stated above but they are that important ;)<BR>
<BR>
1. Be patient. Hunting during peak hours is a pain in the ass anyway, so if you want to be a merchant spend your time in EC instead. If you know what you want, you can find it at a discount price eventually. And if you are there long enough, other excellent buys will present themselves that will definately be profitable. Case in point, I bought 6 different Cane's of the tranquil for 1-1.2k this weekend.<BR>
<BR>
2. Be knowledgable. Just because Shieldstorm is listed at 7.5k on eqprices.com, it does'nt mean you are gonna sell it for that price very easily. Or at all. I had that thing for sale in EC for 2 weeks and never got an offer more then 1k for it. Doh. Until you become more familiar with the market, stick with things you know. Few general tips are 1hs weapons generally move easier then 2hs. Int gear is always popular, but some older int gear (shiny metallic robe for instance) don't have the same market value as it used to, and people are selling for alot less then the items are quoted at. And be friendly to people, they will often tell you what an item they were auctioning actually sold for, especially if you chat with them for awhile. You'll have nothing else to do if you squat down in EC, so make some contacts while you are there.<BR>
<BR>
3. Haggle! People will almost always go down on prices, especially if they have had it on there person for awhile. And if you fancy yourself a hustler, look for marks that you know don't have what it takes to sit in EC for an evening to get a fair price for there wares. The best bets are usually people that are liquidating a twink char, or are auctioning there wares every 3.7 seconds in EC.<BR>
<BR>
4. Trade up. I was selling Solist's icy wand this weekend, and someone really really wanted it. All they had for trade though was an FBSS. I obviously was'nt getting an fbss for this wand, but the wand + cane of the tranquil was begrudgingly accepted because the cane is an easy sell.<BR>
<BR>
5. Play poor. If someone thinks all you have is 1.1k, and they are'nt getting alot of other serious offer's they will seriously consider giving it to you, even if they have been asking 1.5k. I spent alot of time learning techniques to be a good hustler in EC, I might write an article about it some day.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Twist<BR>
The Nameless Huster
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
